{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17488753","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17488753"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T03:55:09+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T03:55:09+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"525"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"525","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/525"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.06,0.65,0.21,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"525"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107888"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"525","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/525"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"525"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90304"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"12"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"42"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"735"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4945"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"9641"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11631"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1714"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1747"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12907"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39888"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39890"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42093"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43016"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45684"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107888","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/107888"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 25-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a dislocated shoulder. She reports that she frequently dislocates her shoulder and does not seem particularly distressed by it. Whilst waiting for further assessment, she shows her favourite \u0027party trick\u0027 (Image). She reports that her father has the same condition as her and she needs to see specialists including a heart specialist for regular follow-up. She also mentions that she has blurry vision and is very short-sighted, requiring strong glasses since childhood. She has no other significant medical history and does not take any regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There is obvious joint hypermobility demonstrated in the image. Visual acuity is reduced at 6/12 in both eyes with correction.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following cardiac abnormalities is a cardinal diagnostic criteria for her condition?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Pulmonary hypertension","Tricuspid regurgitation","Aortic root dilatation","Mitral regurgitation","Ventricular septal defect"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis woman is exhibiting signs of connective tissue disease with frequent shoulder dislocation, excessive joint laxity, and visual symptoms suggestive of ectopia lentis. The image shows gross hyperextension of the thumb joint - a manifestation of the joint hypermobility underlying connective tissue disease. Her reduced visual acuity, myopia, and blurry vision are consistent with lens dislocation. Marfan syndrome is the most common connective tissue disease associated with skeletal, cardiac and ocular manifestations. It is an autosomal dominant connective tissue disorder involving cardiovascular, skeletal and ocular systems, skin, lungs and dura. The two most important clinical features in diagnosing Marfan syndrome according to the revised Ghent criteria are ectopia lentis and \u003Cstrong\u003Eaortic root dilatation\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile Marfan syndrome can be associated with other cardiac complications such as mitral valve prolapse and \u003Cstrong\u003Emitral regurgitation\u003C/strong\u003E, left ventricular dilatation and cardiac failure, and pulmonary artery dilatation, they are not one of the cardinal diagnostic features. These patients also have a future risk of aortic regurgitation and aortic dissection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other listed options (\u003Cstrong\u003Epulmonary hypertension\u003C/strong\u003E, \u003Cstrong\u003Etricuspid regurgitation\u003C/strong\u003E, \u003Cstrong\u003Eventricular septal defect\u003C/strong\u003E) are not associated with Marfan syndrome.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Aortic root dilatation is an important association with Marfan\u0027s syndrome.","Ectopia lentis and aortic root dilatation are the two cardinal diagnostic features of Marfan syndrome according to the revised Ghent criteria.","Joint hypermobility and lens dislocation together with cardiovascular involvement suggest connective tissue disorders like Marfan syndrome."],"references":["Ades L. Guidelines for the diagnosis and management of Marfan syndrome. Heart Lung Circ. 2007;16(1):28-30. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/17188935/","Summers KM, West JA, Hattam A, Stark D, McGill JJ, West MJ. Recent developments in the diagnosis of Marfan syndrome and related disorders. Med J Aust. 2012;197(9):494-7. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/23121584/","Dean JC. Management of Marfan syndrome. Heart. 2002 Jul 1;88(1):97-103. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC1767196/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90304"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"525"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"15158"}]}